00:00:21.246 --> 00:00:22.120
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:24.140
So, we'll get started.

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:27.030
And as I mentioned,
to some degree

00:00:27.030 --> 00:00:31.290
this is going to be review on
the setting of our notation

00:00:31.290 --> 00:00:33.100
and conventions clear.

00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:36.735
So, our first topic is
the Schrodinger equation.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:50.110
So this Schrodinger
equation is an equation

00:00:50.110 --> 00:00:52.340
that takes the following form.

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:56.180
I h bar partial
derivative of this object

00:00:56.180 --> 00:01:03.340
called the wave function
that depends on x and t

00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:09.000
is equal to minus h squared
over 2m second derivative

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:17.103
with respect to x plus v
of x and t Psi of x and t.

00:01:21.450 --> 00:01:22.910
And that's the full equation.

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:24.430
That's the Schrodinger equation.

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:28.460
Now actually, this is not
the Schrodinger equation

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:32.060
in most generality, but it's
the Schrodinger equation

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:35.310
for the case that you
have a potential that

00:01:35.310 --> 00:01:37.960
depends on x and t.

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:41.760
For the case that we are doing
non-relativistic physics,

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:46.560
because this thing you may
remember is p squared over 2m

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.400
is the kinetic energy operator.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:53.380
So p squared over 2m
is non-relativistic.

00:01:53.380 --> 00:01:55.740
That's a non-relativistic
kinetic energy.

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:57.870
So this is non-relativistic.

00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:01.200
Moreover, we have
just one x here.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.460
That means it's a
particle in one dimension.

00:02:04.460 --> 00:02:08.800
So we've done a few things,
but this is generally enough

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:11.530
to illustrate our ideas.

00:02:11.530 --> 00:02:14.560
And the most
important thing that

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:19.190
should be said at
this point is that Psi

00:02:19.190 --> 00:02:27.020
of x and t-- which is
the wave function--

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:29.200
belongs to the complex numbers.

00:02:34.530 --> 00:02:35.980
It's a complex number.

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:38.600
And that's by necessity.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:43.410
If Psi would be real, this
quantity-- the right hand

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:44.760
side-- would be real.

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:47.340
The potential is a real number.

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:51.125
On the left hand side, on the
other hand, if Psi is real,

00:02:51.125 --> 00:02:54.630
its derivative would be real,
and this would be imaginary.

00:02:54.630 --> 00:02:59.620
So, it's just impossible to get
the solution of this equation

00:02:59.620 --> 00:03:02.790
if Psi is real.

00:03:02.790 --> 00:03:08.070
So, Psi complex is really
the fundamental thing

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:11.300
that can be said about
this wave function.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:16.690
Now, you've used complex
numbers in physics all the time,

00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:20.210
and even in electromagnetism,
you use complex numbers.

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:23.900
But you use them really
in an auxiliary way only.

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:29.060
You didn't use them in an
absolutely necessary way.

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:30.860
So, for example.

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:41.630
In E&amp;M, you had an electric
field, for example,

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:44.620
for a circularly polarized wave.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:51.000
And you would write it as this.

00:03:55.330 --> 00:03:56.410
Let me put the z here.

00:04:00.046 --> 00:04:00.545
Zero.

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:14.190
X hat plus y hat--
those are unit vectors.

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:17.440
I is a complex number.

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:19.420
It's the square root of minus 1.

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:24.680
E to the IKZ minus omega t.

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:27.610
You typically wrote
things like that,

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:32.280
but, in fact, you
always meant real part.

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:39.580
An electric field
is a real quantity.

00:04:39.580 --> 00:04:43.740
And the Maxwell's equations
are real equations.

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:46.740
This is a circularly
polarized wave.

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:49.390
And this whole
thing-- by the time

00:04:49.390 --> 00:04:53.280
you take the real part of
this, all these complex numbers

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:55.300
play absolutely no role.

00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:00.370
It's just a neat way of writing
a complicated electric field

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:05.160
in which the x component and the
y component are out of phase,

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:08.370
and that you have a wave at
the same time propagating

00:05:08.370 --> 00:05:10.930
in the z direction.

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:18.090
So this-- in the
here, E is real,

00:05:18.090 --> 00:05:22.780
and all i's are auxiliary.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:31.840
This is completely
different from the case

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:33.590
of the Schrodinger equation.

00:05:33.590 --> 00:05:36.990
This i there is fundamental.

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:40.090
The Psi is the
dynamical variable,

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:42.460
and it has to be complex.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:45.910
So, we make a few remarks
about the Schrodinger equation

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:48.610
to get started.

00:05:48.610 --> 00:05:56.490
First remark is that this
is first order differential

00:05:56.490 --> 00:05:58.750
equation in time.

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:07.020
This has implications.

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.930
Those two derivatives
are maybe--

00:06:09.930 --> 00:06:12.080
for some funny
Hamiltonians, you can

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:15.070
have even more than two
derivatives or more complicated

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:15.800
things.

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:19.740
But definitely there's just
one derivative in time.

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:22.887
So, what this means
is that if you

00:06:22.887 --> 00:06:26.960
know the wave function
all over space,

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:28.940
you can calculate
what it's going

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:31.260
to be a little time later.

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:34.850
Because if you know
it all over space,

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:37.770
you can calculate
this right hand side

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:39.850
and know what is
the time derivative.

00:06:39.850 --> 00:06:41.500
And with the time
derivative, you

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:44.240
can figure it out what
it's going to be later.

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:47.720
A first order differential
equation in time

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:51.020
is something that if you know
the quantity at one time,

00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:52.830
the differential
equation tells you

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.830
what it's going to be later.

00:06:54.830 --> 00:06:59.200
So, that's really sufficient.

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:11.680
Psi of x-- of all x's-- at some
time t naught determines Psi

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:12.720
at all times.

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:20.820
Second property,
fundamental property.

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:22.155
The equation is linear.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:30.100
So, if you have
two solutions, you

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.430
can form a third by
superimposing them,

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:36.780
and you can superimpose them
with complex coefficients.

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:41.110
So, if you have two
solutions, Psi 1 and Psi 2,

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:50.480
then a 1 Psi 1 plus A2
Psi 2 is a solution.

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:54.650
And here the a's belong
to the complex numbers.

00:07:54.650 --> 00:08:00.430
So A 1 and A 2 are
complex numbers.

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:07.300
As far as complex
numbers are concerned,

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:09.550
the first thing you
just need to know

00:08:09.550 --> 00:08:13.210
is the definition of the
length of a complex number.

00:08:13.210 --> 00:08:16.720
So, if you have z, a
typical name people

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:21.210
use for a complex number,
having two components.

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:26.225
A plus ib, where
a and b are real.

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:33.049
There's the definition of
the complex conjugate, which

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:37.049
is a minus ib, and
there's the definition

00:08:37.049 --> 00:08:39.840
of the length of the
complex number, which

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:44.470
is square root of a
squared plus b squared,

00:08:44.470 --> 00:08:48.380
which is the square
root of z times z star.

00:08:54.150 --> 00:08:57.700
So, that's for your
complex number.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:03.790
So, the property that this makes
this into a physical theory

00:09:03.790 --> 00:09:06.860
and goes beyond math
is what you know

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:11.140
is the interpretation of the
wave function as a probability.

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:12.770
So, what do we construct?

00:09:12.770 --> 00:09:20.580
We construct p of x and
t, or sometimes called

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:24.920
the row of x and t as a density.

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:30.330
And it's defined
as Psi star of x t.

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:35.100
Now, here the notation
means this Psi star--

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:38.490
we'd put the star
here-- it really

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:43.600
means Psi of x and
t complex conjugate.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:45.590
You complex conjugate
the wave function.

00:09:45.590 --> 00:09:46.400
And you get that.

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:49.070
We'd put the star here,
and typically don't

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:51.940
put the parentheses, unless
you have to complex conjugate

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:54.040
something that's a
little ambiguous.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:59.960
So, Psi star of x and
t times Psi of x and t.

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:02.495
And this is called the
probability density.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:08.140
Probability density.

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:19.660
And the interpretation is
that if you take p of x and t

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:25.950
and multiply by little dx,
this is the probability

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:41.770
to find the particle in the
interval x comma x plus dx

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:42.720
at time t.

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:50.780
So, this is our
probability density.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:56.600
It's a way to make physics
out of the wave function.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:59.460
It's a postulate.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:02.620
And so the consequence
of this postulate,

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:05.570
since we're describing
just one particle,

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:09.920
is that we must have the
particle as somewhere.

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:22.136
So, if we add the probabilities
that the particle is somewhere

00:11:22.136 --> 00:11:26.646
all over space, this
is the probability

00:11:26.646 --> 00:11:31.350
that the particle is in
this little dx we integrated

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:34.570
that must be equal to 1.

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:36.925
And this must hold
for all times.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:42.950
In terms of things
to notice here,

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:47.650
maybe one thing you can
notice is the units of Psi.

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:53.040
The units of Psi must be 1
over square root of length,

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.860
because when we square it,
then we multiply it by length,

00:11:55.860 --> 00:11:58.605
we get one, which has no units.

00:12:03.710 --> 00:12:07.090
Key property of the
Schrodinger equation.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:12.200
We will revisit the Schrodinger
equation later and derive it,

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.870
sort of the way [? De ?]
[? Rack ?] derives it in his

00:12:14.870 --> 00:12:16.070
textbook.

00:12:16.070 --> 00:12:19.970
As just a consequence of
unitary time evolution,

00:12:19.970 --> 00:12:23.020
it would be a very
neat derivation.

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:25.070
It will give you a
feeling that you really

00:12:25.070 --> 00:12:28.040
understand something deep
about quantum mechanics.

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:32.500
And it will be
true, that feeling.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:35.200
But here, we're going to
go the other way around.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:41.470
Just simply ask the
question-- suppose

00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:51.280
you have a wave function
such that the integral

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:56.915
of this quantity at some
specific time is equal to one.

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:07.230
Will this integral be
equal to one for all times,

00:13:07.230 --> 00:13:12.020
given that it is one
at some given time?

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:15.170
Now, you say, well,
why do you ask that?

00:13:15.170 --> 00:13:18.890
I ask that because actually
this could be a problem.

00:13:18.890 --> 00:13:22.850
We've said that if you know the
wave function all over space

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:25.210
at one time, it's
determined everywhere.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:27.140
So any time later.

00:13:27.140 --> 00:13:31.130
Therefore, if I know the wave
function at time equal zero

00:13:31.130 --> 00:13:35.850
is good-- time equal t zero--
is a good wave function,

00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:39.370
I might warranty that when I
saw the Schrodinger equation,

00:13:39.370 --> 00:13:43.400
the wave function will be
normalized, well, later?

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:44.840
Yes, you are.

00:13:44.840 --> 00:13:48.820
And it's a simple or
interesting exercise

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:52.570
that we'll call it
the quick calculation

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:54.300
that I'll leave
it for you to do.

00:13:57.940 --> 00:14:14.040
Which is show that d dt of
this integral Psi of x and t

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:17.900
squared dx is equal to zero.

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:20.400
So, basically what
this is saying.

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:24.680
You got one but, think of
this integral-- I'm sorry,

00:14:24.680 --> 00:14:29.920
I'm missing a dx here-- think
of this integral for all times.

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:33.650
Now it could be a
function of time,

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:36.310
because you put an
arbitrary time here.

00:14:36.310 --> 00:14:38.660
The integral might
depend on time.

00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:42.600
So, it's a good question to
think of that integral that

00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:45.730
may be a function of time
and take its derivative.

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:49.410
If its derivative is
zero for all times,

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:54.780
and that sometimes equal to
one, it will be one forever.

00:14:54.780 --> 00:14:58.880
So, you must show
that this is true.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:03.240
Now, this I think you've done
one way or another several ways

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:05.270
maybe in 804.

00:15:05.270 --> 00:15:07.220
But I ask you to do it again.

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:11.880
So this is left for you as a
way to warm up on this object.

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:17.260
And you will see actually
that it's a little subtle.

00:15:17.260 --> 00:15:20.880
It's a little delicate,
because how is it going to go?

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:25.430
You're going to go in and take
the derivative of Psi Psi star.

00:15:25.430 --> 00:15:27.219
You're going to take
the derivative of Psi

00:15:27.219 --> 00:15:29.260
and you're going to use
the Schrodinger equation.

00:15:29.260 --> 00:15:31.740
You're going to take the
derivative of Psi star,

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:34.180
and you're going to use
the complex conjugate

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:36.170
of the Schrodinger equation.

00:15:36.170 --> 00:15:37.720
It's going to be a little messy.

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:41.230
But then you're going to
do integration by parts,

00:15:41.230 --> 00:15:44.010
and you're going to get zero,
but only if you throw away

00:15:44.010 --> 00:15:45.650
the terms at infinity.

00:15:45.650 --> 00:15:49.420
And what gives you the
right to throw them away?

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:50.770
You will have to think.

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:54.530
And the answer is that
you will throw them away

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:57.360
if the wave function
goes to zero

00:15:57.360 --> 00:16:02.640
at infinity, which must do it.

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:05.260
The wave function must
go to zero at infinity,

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:07.700
because if it didn't
go to zero at infinity,

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.170
it went to a
constant at infinity,

00:16:10.170 --> 00:16:15.140
it would pick up an
un-normalizable thing here.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:19.200
So the wave function definitely
has to go to zero at infinity.

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:21.870
But that will also
not be quite enough

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:24.600
if you're careful about
what you're doing.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:28.720
You will have to demand that the
derivative of the wave function

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:30.550
doesn't blow up.

00:16:30.550 --> 00:16:34.840
It's not asking too much,
but it's asking something.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.620
A function could go
to zero, presumably,

00:16:37.620 --> 00:16:40.770
and its derivative at
the same time blow up,

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.760
but it would be a very
pathological function.

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.650
This will bring us to
something that we said.

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:50.430
We're going to
try to be precise,

00:16:50.430 --> 00:16:53.340
but it's not so
easy to be precise.

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:56.520
When you try to be
precise, you can

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.040
exaggerate and go
precise to a point

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:02.210
that you're paralyzed with
fear with every equation.

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:04.859
We don't want to get that far.

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:07.750
We want you to notice what
happens and just look at it

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:09.200
and state what you need.

00:17:09.200 --> 00:17:11.770
Why can't we be precise?

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:14.800
Because at the end of
the day, this equation

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:18.170
is extraordinarily
complicated, and maybe crazy.

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:20.640
The potential is crazy enough.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:25.970
So, functions-- mathematicians
can invent crazy functions,

00:17:25.970 --> 00:17:29.920
things like a function that is
one for every rational number

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:32.410
and zero for every
rational number.

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:37.360
Put that for a potential here,
and who knows what one gets.

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:39.530
So, we're going to
take mild functions.

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:42.400
We're not going to make
them a very complicated,

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:45.700
and we're going to be stating
very soon what we need.

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:47.780
So, what you need
for this to work

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:49.850
is that the function
goes to zero

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:51.570
and the relative goes to zero.

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:52.606
Yes.

00:17:52.606 --> 00:17:55.730
AUDIENCE: The potential
has to be real always?

00:17:55.730 --> 00:17:58.070
PROFESSOR: The potential
is real at this moment.

00:17:58.070 --> 00:17:59.250
Yes.

00:17:59.250 --> 00:18:01.550
For the discussion
that we're doing here,

00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:04.688
v is also a real number.

